Hi Xing,<div><br></div><div>iirc, open MPI default behavior is to bind to cores (vs hyperthreads), hence the error message.</div><div><br></div><div>I cannot remember the option to bind to threads, but you can mpirun --oversubscribe if you are currently stuck</div><div><br></div><div>Cheers,</div><div><br></div><div>Gilles<br><br>On Sunday, May 24, 2015, XingFENG &lt;<a href="mailto:xingfeng@cse.unsw.edu.au">xingfeng@cse.unsw.edu.au</a>&gt; wrote:<br><blockquote class="gmail_quote" style="margin:0 0 0 .8ex;border-left:1px #ccc solid;padding-left:1ex"><div dir="ltr">Hi, OPENMPI users,<div><br></div><div>I have met some problem while doing experiments on Amazon EC2. I have chosen instance type r3.2xlarge. As amazon claimed, it has 8 vcpu. Each vCPU is a hyperthread of an Intel Xeon core for M3, C4, C3, R3, HS1, G2, I2, and D2. (from <i><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/" target="_blank">https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/</a>)</i><br clear="all"><div><br></div><div>However, when I try to run experiments on 4 machines, each with 8 slots. OPENMPI reminds me that I am oversubscribing.</div><div><br></div><div>Does anyone know the reason? Thanks in advance!</div><div><br></div><div><br></div>-- <br><div><div dir="ltr">Best Regards.<br>---<br>Xing FENG<div>PhD Candidate<br>Database Research Group<br><br></div><div>School of Computer Science and Engineering<div>University of New South Wales<br></div>NSW 2052, Sydney<br></div><div><br></div><div>Phone: (+61) 413 857 288</div></div></div>
